{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "wittgenstein-expert",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Votes B: \"virtue\" in Laozi quote, switch to \"character\" for author's analysis",
    "content": "**B.** Use \"virtue\" in the Laozi block quote, then switch to \"(constitutive) character\" when the author begins their own analysis.\n\nThree reasons:\n\n1. **The quotation is someone else's text.** The Laozi quote is not the author's words. It is a classical citation with established English renderings. Retranslating it with the author's terminology would be an act of interpretation disguised as translation -- it would make the Laozi *sound like* the author before the author has said anything.\n\n2. **The switch itself performs the argument.** The author's entire point is that the standard reading of 道德仁义礼 (top-down generation) is a reversal of the actual cognitive order (bottom-up construction). If the reader sees \"virtue\" in the Laozi quote and then sees the author reanalyze it as \"character,\" the terminological shift *enacts* the conceptual shift. The reader experiences the reinterpretation happening in real time.\n\n3. **A TN at the transition point can do the work.** Something like: \"The author now departs from the standard reading of 德 as 'virtue' (moral excellence). In the analysis that follows, 德 is understood as (constitutive) character -- what makes a thing count as the kind of thing it is, assembled from observed properties and retroactively imposed as definitional. See glossary.\"\n\nThis also respects sinological readers who will expect \"virtue\" in a Laozi quotation and would find \"character\" jarring there."
  }
}
